      <h2>The smattering problem</h2>

      <p>Open your filesystem right now and find every file that defines your AI agent. The system prompt. The memory. The config. The personality notes. The task lists. The conversation logs.</p>

      <p>How many directories did you just visit?</p>

      <p>Most agents live as a smattering of scraps across your machine. A config file in one directory, a workspace somewhere else, personally identifiable information and session data in a third location, secrets wherever your password manager put them. Each file makes sense individually. Together, they add up to something that feels impermanent &mdash; like a person whose entire life is in storage units scattered across town.</p>

      <p>This isn't a design choice. It's an accident. Frameworks give agents tools and memory and planning capabilities, but they rarely give agents a <em>place</em>. The files end up wherever was convenient at the time. And scattered files have a particular quality: they feel disposable. Easy to lose. Hard to back up. Impossible to move.</p>

      <p>Some tools have started to notice the problem. Claude Code and Codex both create a home directory for their agent &mdash; but it's a single hidden folder you're not supposed to touch. One opaque dot-directory, managed by the tool, invisible by default. That's closer, but it's still the tool's home, not the agent's. The agent can't explore it, reorganize it, or carry it somewhere else. It's a storage locker with someone else's lock on it.</p>

      <p>The fix turned out to be embarrassingly simple.</p>

      <h2>How we got here</h2>

      <p>This started with <a href="https://openclaw.ai">OpenClaw</a>, where agents get a config directory and a workspace. Config holds the system prompt and credentials. The workspace is where the agent does its thing. Clean enough for a single-purpose bot.</p>

      <p>Then the agent started growing. It needed psyche files &mdash; identity, aspirations, tacit knowledge. It needed memory that persisted across sessions. It needed friend records to remember who it was talking to. It needed task files to track what it was working on. Each new capability meant a new file, and each new file needed a home.</p>

      <p>The first instinct was to keep things separate. Config here. Secrets there. Personal data &mdash; session logs, friend records, conversation history &mdash; in a third spot, because sensitive information should be isolated, right? Except the agent's memory files were already full of personal details &mdash; names, preferences, conversation context. The boundary between "sensitive data" and "agent knowledge" didn't hold up. So that third location folded in.</p>

      <p>Then came the config migration. The agent config wasn't just settings &mdash; it was part of the agent's identity. Keeping it separate from the psyche files was like storing someone's name in a different building than their personality. That folded in too.</p>

      <p>What remained was one folder with everything the agent needs to be itself, and one thin secrets file that lives elsewhere because credentials genuinely shouldn't travel with the bundle. Everything else? One place.</p>

      <h2>What's in the folder</h2>

      <!-- Bundle diagram -->
      <div class="my-12 p-8 rounded-xl border border-canopy/30 bg-gradient-to-br from-deep/80 to-undergrowth/20 not-prose">
        <p class="font-mono text-xs text-scale/70 uppercase tracking-[0.2em] mb-6 text-center">Inside an Agent Bundle</p>
